    "name": "JSONPlaceholder",
    "description": "This folder shows how I practiced a **full CRUD workflow** (Create, Read, Update, Delete) using the free [JSONPlaceholder](https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/) API.  \nIt’s a fake REST API that’s great for testing because you can send real HTTP requests, but nothing actually changes on the server.\n\nHere’s what I included:\n\n**GET Post by ID** – fetches a single post (for example `/posts/1`) and checks if the response has the right fields like `id` and `title`.\n\n**POST Create New Post** – simulates creating a new post. The data isn’t really saved, but the API pretends it was. I added tests to handle both `200` and `201` responses, since the service isn’t always consistent.\n\n**PUT Update Post** – updates an existing post (like `/posts/1`). I verify that the updated fields are echoed back in the response.\n\n**DELETE Post** – simulates deleting a post. Again, nothing is actually deleted, but I check that the API responds with the expected status code (`200` or `204`).\n\n### What I’m testing\n\nThe correct **status codes** are returned. The **JSON structure** includes expected properties.The **response time** is reasonable (under 1000 ms).\n\n### A note\n\nSince JSONPlaceholder is just a demo API, the requests don’t really change data. Sometimes it even returns `200` instead of `201` for POST requests. I adapted my tests so they still make sense in this context.",
    "schema": "https://schema.getpostman.com/json/collection/v2.1.0/collection.json",
    "_exporter_id": "48214638"
  },
